# React Component Rules

## Component Naming
- Component names must start with a capital letter
- File names for React components must match the main component name
- Use PascalCase for component names (e.g., `UserProfile`, `CourseCard`)

## Component Structure
- Each component should have only one default export
- All components must have PropTypes or TypeScript interfaces
- Use TypeScript interfaces for type definitions instead of PropTypes when possible

## Performance Rules
- Do not declare inline functions in JSX - use useCallback hook instead
- Example of what NOT to do:
  ```jsx
  <Button onPress={() => handleClick()} />
  ```
- Example of what TO do:
  ```jsx
  const handleClick = useCallback(() => {
    // handle click logic
  }, [dependencies]);
  
  <Button onPress={handleClick} />
  ```

## Code Quality
- No console.log statements in production code
- Use proper logging mechanisms or remove debug statements before committing

## File Organization
- React component files should be named exactly as the main component
- Example: Component `UserProfile` should be in file `UserProfile.tsx`
- Place components in appropriate directories based on their purpose

## TypeScript Guidelines
- Always define interfaces for component props
- Use proper typing for all function parameters and return values
- Example:
  ```tsx
  interface UserProfileProps {
    userId: string;
    name: string;
    email: string;
  }
  
  const UserProfile: React.FC<UserProfileProps> = ({ userId, name, email }) => {
    // component implementation
  };
  ```

## Import/Export Rules
- Use named imports when importing multiple items from the same module
- Use default export only for the main component
- Example:
  ```tsx
  import React, { useCallback, useState } from 'react';
  import { Button, Text } from 'react-native';
  
  const MyComponent: React.FC<Props> = (props) => {
    // component implementation
  };
  
  export default MyComponent;
  ```